Background :¶

The "Sporting Goods Sales Data" shows sales of top 5 brands of the company in the first quarter of year 2023. The data also gives quarterly growth for these top 5 brands. The company has presence across the country and the data is available by Region-City.

Objective :¶

Perform PCA on the provided sales data for the top 5 brands in the first quarter of year 2023, categorized by Region and City_Code. The goal is to reduce the dimensionality of the dataset while preserving the key information and identifying any underlying patterns or relationships among the variables

In [46]:
df = data.copy()
# Calculate the correlation matrix
correlation_matrix = df.corr()

# Create a pair plot
g = sns.pairplot(df, diag_kind='kde', markers='o')

# Add coefficient numbers to the plots
for i, j in zip(*plt.np.triu_indices_from(g.axes, 1)):
    g.axes[i, j].annotate(f"Corr: {correlation_matrix.iloc[i, j]:.2f}", (0.5, 0.9), xycoords='axes fraction', ha='center', fontsize=20)

# Show the plot
plt.show()

Dimensionality Reduction with PCA¶

In [47]:
# Drop the 'Region' and 'City_Code' columns as they are not needed for PCA
sporting_data = data.drop(['Region', 'City_Code'], axis=1)
# Standardize the data by scaling it
standardisedX = scale(sporting_data)
# Create a DataFrame from the standardized data
X = pd.DataFrame(standardisedX, index=sporting_data.index, columns=sporting_data.columns)
# Initialize a PCA model and fit it to the standardized data
pca = PCA().fit(X)
# Generate names for the principal components (PC1, PC2, ..., PC10)
names = ["PC" + str(i) for i in range(1, 11)]
# Calculate the standard deviation of each principal component
SD = list(np.std(pca.transform(X), axis=0))
# Calculate the proportion of explained variance for each principal component
VarProp = list(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)
# Calculate the cumulative proportion of explained variance
CumProp = [np.sum(VarProp[:i]) for i in range(1, 11)]
# Create a summary DataFrame with the results
summary = pd.DataFrame(list(zip(SD, VarProp, CumProp)), index=names, columns=['Standard Deviation', 'Proportion of Variance', 'Cumulative Proportion'])
summary

Observation :¶

First Principal Component explains 83% of the variation. The first two components (PC1 and PC2) capture approximately 89.63% of the total variance, and the first five components (PC1 to PC5) capture around 97.02%. This means that the majority of the data's variability can be explained by a relatively small number of principal components.

Scores Based on PCA¶

In [49]:
# Fit PCA and transform the standardized data (X) into principal component scores
Score = PCA().fit_transform(X)

# Create a DataFrame from the principal component scores and set appropriate row and column indices
Score_df = pd.DataFrame(Score, index=data.index, columns=col)

# Assign the values of the first principal component (Comp1) as a new 'performance' column in the original dataset
data = data.assign(performance=Score_df.Comp1)
data['performance'] = data['performance'].round(3)
data.head()

Scree Plot : plot the principal components vs. variances¶

In [50]:
y = np.std(pca.transform(X), axis=0)**2
x = np.arange(len(y)) + 1
plt.plot(x, y, "o-")
plt.xticks(x, ["Comp."+str(i) for i in x], rotation=60)
plt.ylabel("Variance")
plt.show()

Observation :¶

First Principal Component is sufficient in explaining the maximum variation.

Summarizing Performance By Region¶

In [51]:
# Group the data by region and calculate the average performance for each region
average_performance_by_region = data.groupby('Region')['performance'].mean().reset_index()
colors = sns.color_palette("pastel")

# Create a bar graph using the specified color palette
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
#Plotting bar graph
sns.barplot(data=average_performance_by_region, x='Region', y='performance', palette=colors)
plt.title('Average Performance by Region')
plt.xlabel('Region')
plt.ylabel('Average Performance')
plt.xticks(rotation=0)
plt.show()

Observation :¶

The data suggests significant regional variations in performance indicator. "WEST" stands out with the highest positive value, indicating superior performance, while "EAST" has the lowest negative value, implying below-average performance.
